ce:section.ce:para:
GQD-based materials (i.e., GQDs, N-GQDs, amino-GQDs, and amino-N-GQDs) were prepared using a modified Hummers' method (Fig. 2
                      and Figs. S1–S10) (Hummers and Offeman, 1958). As mentioned, the EWD PL emission of GQD-based materials is likely due to a combination of the quantum confinement effect, which is caused by the size of sp2 domains, and the existence of zigzag edge sites and surface effect states (Gong et al., 2019; Sun et al., 2020). Size-selective sieving is a technique that separates materials on the basis of their particle sizes. In this study, the GQD-based materials were sorted using membranes with pores of various sizes (i.e., 1, 5, 8, and 300 kD) to obtain sorted GQD-based materials with different mean lateral sizes. Specifically, the GQDs were sorted into the following size groups: GQD0.7, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 0.7 ± 0.1 nm; GQD4.8, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 4.8 ± 0.2 nm; and GQD12.2, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 12.2 ± 0.2 nm. The N-GQDs were also sorted into the following size groups: N-GQD0.8, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 0.8 ± 0.1 nm; N-GQD4.9, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 4.9 ± 0.2 nm; and N-GQD12.2, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 12.2 ± 0.3 nm. Moreover, the amino-GQDs were sorted into the following size groups: amino-GQD0.8, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 0.8 ± 0.1 nm; amino-GQD5.0, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 5.0 ± 0.3 nm; and amino-GQD12.3, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 12.3 ± 0.2 nm. Finally, the amino-N-GQDs were sorted into the following size groups: amino-N-GQD0.9, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 0.9 ± 0.1 nm; amino-N-GQD5.0, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 5.0 ± 0.2 nm; and amino-N-GQD12.3, comprising materials with a mean lateral size of 12.3 ± 0.4 nm. Subsequently, the materials were analyzed using low-magnification transmission electron microscopy (TEM; Fig. S1) and high-resolution TEM (HR-TEM; Fig. 3
                     ). The HR-TEM results were consistent with the Raman spectroscopy results (Fig. S6), which indicated that the sorted dots had been successfully prepared. Other relevant characterization results also supported this conclusion (Figs. S7–S10). The surface chemistry of the sorted dots was analyzed using X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS), which revealed that the O/C and N/C atomic ratios were in the ranges 0.32–0.47 and 0.049–0.062, respectively. These values indicated that the sorted GQD-based materials had similar degrees of surface oxidation and that they exhibited a homogeneous distribution of O or N dopant functionality as well as high crystallinity and uniformity (Figs. S7–S10). Furthermore, the concentrations of functional groups such as C–C/C=C, C–N, amino–N, pyrrolic–N, and amide–N groups increased with particle size. Similarly, the concentration of pyrrolic–N increased with particle size, and the oxidized interaction occurred mainly in six– or five–membered aromatic heterocycles. By contrast, the concentrations of functional groups such as C–O, C=O, O=C–O, pyridine–N, quaternary–N, and amide–N increased as the particle size decreased, possibly because of the increase in the effects of edge sites. This finding suggests that the number of O– and N–based groups can influence the O and N content. UV–visible (vis) absorption spectra of the sorted GQD-based materials were obtained, and the maximum and edge absorbance peaks in these spectra were analyzed. For GQD0.7, GQD4.8, and GQD12.2, normalized maximal absorbance peaks corresponding to the π–π* transition of aromatic C=C bonds (sp2 domains) were observed at approximately 218, 337, and 581 nm, respectively, and edge absorbance peaks corresponding to the n–π* transition of the C=O shoulder were observed at approximately 322, 440, and 632 nm, respectively (Fig. S11a). Similarly, for N-GQD0.8, N-GQD4.9, and N-GQD12.2, peaks corresponding to the π–π* transition of aromatic C=C bonds (sp2 domains) were observed at approximately 222, 340, and 584 nm, respectively, and peaks corresponding to the n–π* transition of the C=O shoulder and C–N were observed at approximately 325, 445, and 636 nm, respectively. For amino-GQD0.8, amino-GQD5.0, and amino-GQD12.3, normalized maximal absorbance peaks corresponding to the π–π* transition were observed at 224, 342, and 585 nm, respectively, and edge absorbance peaks corresponding to the n–π* transition were observed at 326, 446, and 637 nm, respectively. For amino-N-GQD0.9, amino-N-GQD5.0, and amino-N-GQD12.3, normalized maximal absorbance peaks corresponding to the π–π* transition were observed at 229, 345, and 588 nm, respectively, and edge absorbance peaks corresponding to the n–π* transition were observed at 330, 449, and 641 nm, respectively (Figs. S11b–d). A PL spectrometer was used to investigate the sorted GQD-based materials under excitation by light whose wavelengths were in the UV to the NIR-I regions. The PL spectra showed that the PL peaks of the sorted GQD-based materials exhibited a red shift from the UV to the NIR-I region, with the wavelengths corresponding to the peaks varying depending on the type of GQD. Specifically, for GQD0.7, GQD4.8, and GQD12.2, the PL peaks were observed at approximately 371, 545, and 848 nm, respectively. For N-GQD0.8, N-GQD4.9, and N-GQD12.2, the PL peaks were observed at approximately 374, 551, and 854 nm, respectively. For amino-GQD0.8, amino-GQD5.0, and amino-GQD12.3, the PL peaks were observed at approximately 376, 553, and 857 nm, respectively. Finally, for amino-N-GQD0.9, amino-N-GQD5.0, and amino-N-GQD12.3, the PL peaks were observed at approximately 380, 558, and 863 nm, respectively (Fig. S12). The red shift of the PL peaks to a longer wavelength suggests that the electronic transitions occurred at lower energy levels. These transitions may have been due to the presence of N and/or amino functional groups within the GQDs; this is because the addition of these atoms and/or amino functional groups modified the dots' electronic properties and led to different PL behaviors. The PL spectra of all sorted GQD-based materials revealed EWI-PL, and the PL emissions were determined to be due to radiative π*–n transitions (Li et al., 2021). The insets in Fig. 3 present images of the dispersive sorted GQD-based materials exhibiting varying levels of PL across UV to NIR-I wavelengths ranging from 365 nm (smallest and medium-size GQDs, green) to 633 nm (largest GQDs, gray-level image). The normalized PL excitation (PLE) spectra (Fig. S13) indicated that the excitation wavelengths that resulted in the maximal local PL emission corresponded to the wavelengths of the peaks in the PL spectra (Fig. S12). Deconvolution of the PLE spectra revealed three absorptive transition peaks, which were ascribed to different electronic transitions. Specifically, the long-wavelength peak with an energy value slightly smaller than that of PL emission was ascribed to the n→π* transition; the intermediate-wavelength peak with an energy value close to that of the absorbance maximum was ascribed to the π→π* transition; and the short-wavelength peak with high energy was ascribed to the n→σ* transition. Additionally, UV photoelectron spectroscopy (UPS) was applied to determine the highest occupied orbital level of the sorted GQD-based materials. The UPS results indicated that the energy levels of the located n-state levels exhibited the expected relative similarity for all GQD sizes (Fig. S14). Particle size affected the wavelengths of radiative transitions due to quantum confinement. However, the sorted GQD-based materials exhibited EWI-PL emissions, indicating the absence of trap states between the n-state and π* energy levels. The n-state level was almost unaffected by particle size, whereas the π, π*, and σ* orbital levels were discovered to be strongly affected by particle size. The EWI-PL emissions exhibited by the sorted dots were attributed to π*→n recombination involving an electron transition and phonon scattering. Furthermore, the relaxation of electrons from the σ* orbital to the π* orbital was discovered to be essential to the PL induced through short-wavelength excitation. This finding suggests that the dots’ size and chemical composition influenced the electronic transitions and relaxation pathways in the sorted dots. Schematics of the energy levels corresponding to the absorption and PL of the sorted GQD-based materials are presented in Fig. S15. These results thus demonstrate the successful preparation of sorted GQD-based materials with EDI-PL.
